{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513941"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:16:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:16:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12253"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12253"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.79,0.03,0.01,0.17,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4775"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78581"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4775"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12253"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63923"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1498"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"5789"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42723"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78581"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with a 10 day history of recurrent headaches and jaw pain. The pain only occurs on the right side of her head and extends down to her ear and jaw. The pain is sudden in onset, may last 1-2 minutes and has been occurring several times a day. The pain is excruciating and feels like an electric shock. It appears whenever she tries to eat food. Her only past medical history is hayfever for which she takes antihistamines PRN. One examination her blood pressure is 135/85mmHg, pulse rate 86/min and temperature 37.3\u02daC. The physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trigeminal neuralgia","Cluster headache","Migraine","Giant cell arteritis","Tension headaches"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is presenting with \u003Cstrong\u003Etrigeminal neuralgia \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich is described as a short-lived, lightning-shock pain in the facial region or the jaw. The pain occurs regularly and usually lasts for anywhere between 1-5 minutes and ends spontaneously. It is not associated with any autonomic symptoms like lacrimation or rhinorrhoea. The pain in trigeminal neuralgia is always triggered by some movement of the face like chewing food, yawning, or shaving. In this patient the trigger is eating food.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECluster headache\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by unilateral headache or eye pain which occurs intermittently, the patient usually has a symptom-free interval which can last for weeks or months and then they will present with attacks of headaches at a rate of 20-30 in a day for 2-3 days time period. It is associated with autonomic symptoms and signs like lacrimation, rhinorrhea and Horner\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiant cell arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents in the elderly population with a universal pulsatile type of headache associated with tenderness in the temple region, elevated ESR and CRP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETension headaches\u003C/strong\u003E are one of the most common causes of headaches in the general population, they usually occur due to some stressful conditions but are not short-lived, they occur throughout the day and get worse with exercise, the patient describes them as a bilateral pain that radiates to the neck or a tension band that is wrapped around their head. They are treated by using NSAIDs and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigraine headaches\u003C/strong\u003E are unilateral, pulsatile and can last for anywhere between 24-48 hours if they are not successfully relieved. They are commonly associated with photophobia, nausea, and vomiting and are sometimes triggered by identifiable trigger e.g. coffee, chocolates, menstrual cycle. The patient usually has a history of headaches. They can be relieved by sleep and followed by a \u0022hang-over\u0022 period on the next day. Triptans are pharmacological agents used to relieve acute attacks and a variety of medications e.g. beta- blockers, calcium channel blockers can be used as migraine prophylaxis\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trigeminal neuralgia is a sudden, short-lived, unilateral pain in the facial region.","The pain in trigeminal neuralgia is often triggered by activities such as eating, talking, or touching the face."],"references":["Robbins MS. Diagnosis and Management of Headache: A Review. JAMA. 2021 May 11;325(18):1874-1885. doi: 10.1001/jama.2021.1640. PMID: 33974014. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33974014/","Maarbjerg S, Di Stefano G, Bendtsen L, Cruccu G. Trigeminal neuralgia - diagnosis and treatment. Cephalalgia. 2017 Jun;37(7):648-657. doi: 10.1177/0333102416687280. Epub 2017 Jan 11. PMID: 28076964. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28076964/","Lambru G, Zakrzewska J, Matharu M. Trigeminal neuralgia: a practical guide. Pract Neurol. 2021 Oct;21(5):392-402. doi: 10.1136/practneurol-2020-002782. Epub 2021 Jun 9. PMID: 34108244; PMCID: PMC8461413. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34108244/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63923"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12253"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63923"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T16:58:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T17:00:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4775"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78581"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"